# DOC 1 — PROJECTS & TASKS
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

**Agent scope:** Build or audit Projects/Tasks database system, configure sprints, set up task views, write agent SOPs for project-level automation.
**Agents must not:** Delete entries, change permissions, restructure source databases, or modify sprint configurations without explicit instruction.

---

## 1.1 The Four-Database Foundation

| Database | What it holds | Parent/child |
|---|---|---|
| **Projects** | Discrete bodies of work with a defined outcome and timeline | Parent of Tasks |
| **Tasks** | Individual actionable work items with a single owner | Child of Projects; child of Sprints (if using) |
| **Sprints** | Time-boxed containers grouping tasks across projects | Parent of Tasks |
| **Domain DB** | One context-specific database (content, CRM, assets, etc.) | Relates to Projects or Tasks as needed |

**Rule:** Projects are parents of Tasks. Tasks belong to exactly one Project and optionally one Sprint — never more than one of either.

**When to skip Sprints:** Only when running time-boxed iterative work — engineering, content production, or workflows with explicit planning cycles.

---

## 1.2 Projects Database — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Project Name` | Title | Outcome-oriented verb phrase |
| `Project Status` | Status | Lifecycle state |
| `Project Owner` | Person | Accountable individual |
| `Project Start Date` | Date | Planned or actual start |
| `Project Due Date` | Date | Target completion |
| `Project Priority` | Select | High / Medium / Low |
| `Project ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `PROJ-`) | Stable reference for agents and relations |
| `Tasks` | Relation → Tasks DB | Links all child tasks |
| `Task Progress` | Rollup → Tasks (% Complete) | Calculated from task Status groups |

### Status groups for Projects
```
To-do:        Planned, Backlog
In progress:  Active, On Hold
Complete:     Done, Cancelled
```

### Optional properties

| Property | Type | When to add |
|---|---|---|
| `Project Type` | Select | Campaign, Infrastructure, Research |
| `Project Collaborators` | Person | Multi-person teams |
| `Related Projects` | Relation → Projects DB (self) | Dependent or sequential projects |

**Rollup pattern:** `% of tasks where Status group = Complete` — survives status option changes because it uses group semantics, not option names.

---

## 1.3 Tasks Database — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Task Name` | Title | Verb + specific deliverable |
| `Task Status` | Status | Workflow state |
| `Task Owner` | Person | Single responsible owner |
| `Task Due Date` | Date | When this task must be done |
| `Project` | Relation → Projects DB | Parent project — one per task |
| `Task ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `TASK-`) | Stable reference for agents |
| `Sprint` | Relation → Sprints DB | Optional — only if using sprints |
| `Priority` | Select | High / Medium / Low |

### Status groups for Tasks
```
To-do:        Not Started, Backlog
In progress:  In Progress, In Review, Blocked
Complete:     Done, Cancelled
```

`Blocked` belongs under **In progress** — a blocked task is active; it is being monitored and needs action to unblock.

### Naming convention — non-negotiable
**Verb + specific deliverable**

| Good | Bad |
|---|---|
| `Draft Q2 campaign brief` | `Campaign` |
| `Fix OBS scene transition bug` | `Bug fix` |
| `Review Luiz's overlay design` | `Review` |
| `Send Carson contract follow-up` | `Carson` |

---

## 1.4 The Task Database Designation
`Source: Official | Last verified: Mar 4, 2026 | Confidence: High`

**How to enable:**
1. Open database settings (⋯)
2. Database settings → More settings → Turn into Tasks
3. Map: Status → `Task Status`, Assignee → `Task Owner`, Due date → `Task Due Date`

**What it unlocks:** Home → My Tasks aggregation · Sprint configuration · Sub-tasks and Dependencies settings · Notion Calendar task layer integration

**One-way designation:** Cannot easily undo without losing sprint configuration. Decide before building the schema.

---

## 1.5 Sub-tasks and Dependencies

### Sub-tasks
- Enabled via Database settings → More settings → Sub-items
- Use when: a task has 3–7 discrete steps needing individual tracking, or steps need different assignees
- Do not use when: steps are really separate tasks, or sub-tasks need to relate to different Projects

### Dependencies
- Directional arrows in Timeline view only
- **Hard constraint:** Only visible in Timeline view; require Date properties on both tasks
- **Agent note:** Dependencies are not readable/writable via standard database operations. Use a `Blocked By` Relation property as an agent-readable proxy.

---

## 1.6 Sprints — Architecture and Setup
`Source: Official | Last verified: Mar 4, 2026 | Confidence: High`

**How to enable:** Database must already be a Task database → Database settings → More settings → Sprints → Turn on → Set sprint duration → Notion creates Sprints DB and Sprint board automatically.

### The four Sprint board views

| View | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Current Sprint** | Daily execution — what's on deck right now |
| **Sprint Planning** | Planning sessions — drag tasks into sprints |
| **Backlog** | Grooming — prioritize and assign upcoming work |
| **Timeline** | Review cadence — see sprint sequencing and gaps |

**Completing a sprint:** Choose consciously whether to move incomplete tasks to next sprint or to backlog. Defaulting to "move to next sprint" without reviewing causes sprint bloat.

### Sprint schema additions

| Property | Type | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Sprint Goal` | Text | One sentence per sprint |
| `Sprint Status` | Status | Planned / Active / Complete |
| `Velocity` | Rollup → Tasks (Count where Done) | Tracks completed tasks per sprint |

---

## 1.7 Views — Project & Task Configuration

### Projects database

| View | Configuration | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Board** | Group by `Project Status` | See all projects by lifecycle stage |
| **Table** | Sort by `Project Due Date` | Bulk editing |
| **Timeline** | Date range = `Project Start Date` → `Project Due Date` | Planning and scheduling |
| **My Projects** | Filter: `Project Owner = Me`, Status group ≠ Complete | Personal focus |

### Tasks database

| View | Configuration | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Board** | Group by `Task Status` | Daily execution |
| **My Tasks** | Filter: `Task Owner = Me`, Status group ≠ Complete, sort by `Task Due Date` | Personal focus |
| **By Project** | Group by `Project` relation | All tasks under each project |
| **Overdue** | Filter: `Task Due Date` before today, Status group ≠ Complete | Weekly review |
| **Timeline** | Date = `Task Due Date`, dependencies enabled | Sprint planning |

**Linked view on project pages:** Inside each Project page body, add a linked view of the Tasks database filtered to `Project = [this project]`. Type `/linked` → "Linked view of database" → Tasks → filter `Project = [current page]`. This is the single most useful structural decision in the Projects/Tasks system — every project page becomes a live command center.

---

## 1.8 Page Body Standards — Projects and Tasks

### Project page body template
```
## What This Project Is
[2-3 sentences: what we're building, why it matters, what success looks like]

## Outcome / Definition of Done
[One clear statement of what "complete" means]

## Key Constraints
[Dates, dependencies, budget, team limitations]

## Context for AI
[Background an agent needs to act without asking for clarification]

---
[Linked view: Tasks filtered to this project]
```

### Task page body template
```
## What This Task Is
[1-2 sentences: what needs to be done and why]

## Definition of Done
[Specific, unambiguous — what does "complete" look like?]

## Notes / Context
[Links, blockers, decisions made, prior attempts]
```

**Rule:** If a task page body is empty, an agent cannot act on it reliably. Body content is not documentation overhead — it is agent fuel.

---

## 1.9 Agent SOP Templates — Project Automation

### SOP 1: Daily Task Digest
```
SOP: Task Digest Agent — Daily Summary
Goal: Post summary of all tasks due today or overdue to designated Slack channel
Inputs: Tasks database, filtered: Status group ≠ Complete, Due Date ≤ today | Slack channel: [specify]
Allowed actions: Read Tasks database (filtered view) | Post formatted message to Slack
Hard constraints: Read only — no writes | No DMs — channel only | If 0 tasks: post "No tasks due today."
Validation: [ ] Filter returns results | [ ] Message includes Task Name, Owner, Due Date, Project
Logging: Agent Log: timestamp, task count, Slack post confirmed
Escalation: If Slack post fails → create Agent Inbox item
```

### SOP 2: Overdue Task Flagging
```
SOP: Overdue Flag Agent — Status Updater
Goal: Update Task Status to "Blocked" for tasks where Due Date is past and Status is "In Progress"
Inputs: Tasks database, filtered: Due Date < today, Task Status = "In Progress"
Allowed actions: Update Task Status to "Blocked" | Append to page body: "[Agent] Flagged overdue on [date]. Was: In Progress."
Hard constraints: Do not change Status if already Blocked, Done, or Cancelled | No deletes | Always log before acting
Validation: [ ] Due Date genuinely past | [ ] Status is "In Progress" only | [ ] Task has an Owner
Logging: Agent Log: task ID, name, previous status, new status, timestamp
Escalation: If Owner missing → skip, add to Agent Inbox
```

### SOP 3: Sprint Rollover Summary
```
SOP: Sprint Summary Agent — End of Sprint Report
Goal: When sprint ends, generate summary: tasks completed, moved, cancelled
Inputs: Sprints database: sprint with Status = "Complete" (most recent) | Tasks database: filtered to that sprint's relation
Allowed actions: Read Sprints and Tasks databases | Create page in Sprint Retrospectives database | Post summary to Slack
Hard constraints: Read only on Sprints and Tasks | Write only to Sprint Retrospectives | Do not modify any task or sprint properties
Validation: [ ] Confirm sprint Status = "Complete" | [ ] Tasks relation is populated
Logging: Agent Log: sprint name, date, task counts (complete / moved / cancelled)
Escalation: If sprint has 0 tasks → skip and log, do not post
```

---

## 1.10 Common Mistakes — Projects & Tasks

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Using Select instead of Status | Group filtering breaks; agents can't reason about state | Switch to Status; map options to correct groups |
| Not enabling Task database designation | Tasks don't appear in Home; Sprints can't be turned on | Enable via Database settings → Turn into Tasks |
| Tasks with no Project relation | Orphaned tasks; no rollup progress | Make Project relation required in page template |
| Vague task names | Unsearchable; agents produce low-quality outputs | Enforce Verb + deliverable naming at creation |
| Empty task page bodies | Autofill and agents have no context | Add body template as default in DB settings |
| Building sub-tasks when separate tasks are needed | Sub-tasks can't have independent Project relations | Use Tasks + relation if items need separate project ownership |
| Adding sprints before Task DB designation | Sprints option doesn't appear in settings | Designate as Task database first |
| Rollup counting option names instead of groups | Breaks when options are renamed | Use Status group = Complete in rollup |

---

---

# DOC 2 — CRM
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

**Agent scope:** Build or audit Contacts/Companies/Deals database system, configure pipeline stages, set up relationship views, write agent SOPs for contact enrichment and follow-up automation.
**Agents must not:** Delete contact records, modify pipeline stages, send communications on behalf of the workspace owner, or alter company records without explicit instruction.

**Honest scope statement:** Notion CRM is powerful for relationship context, pipeline visibility, and AI-enriched contact management. Not a replacement for HubSpot/Salesforce/Attio when you need email tracking, call logging, or complex automation at scale.

---

## 2.1 CRM Architecture — Decision Ladder

Build in order. Only add the next layer when the current one is genuinely operational.

| Layer | Database | Add when... |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Contacts** | You have relationships to track |
| 2 | **Companies** | Multiple contacts share an organization |
| 3 | **Deals** | You run multiple business cycles with the same companies |
| 4 | **Interactions** | Volume or multi-user context requires structured touchpoint logging |

---

## 2.2 Contacts Database — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Contact Name` | Title | Full name — Last, First for sortability |
| `Contact Status` | Status | Relationship lifecycle state |
| `Company` | Relation → Companies DB | Employer or affiliated organization |
| `Role` | Text | Job title or role |
| `Email` | Email | Primary contact email |
| `Phone` | Phone | Primary phone number |
| `Contact Type` | Multi-select | Client / Prospect / Partner / Vendor / Collaborator / Personal |
| `Contact Owner` | Person | Who manages this relationship |
| `Contact ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `CON-`) | Stable reference for agents |
| `Last Contacted` | Date | Most recent outreach or interaction |
| `Next Follow-up` | Date | Scheduled next touch |

### Status groups for Contacts
```
To-do:        New, To Qualify
In progress:  Active, Nurturing, In Negotiation
Complete:     Client, Inactive, Archived
```

### Optional properties

| Property | Type | When to add |
|---|---|---|
| `LinkedIn` | URL | When outreach or social context matters |
| `Source` | Select | Referral / Event / Inbound / Cold / Personal |
| `Deals` | Relation → Deals DB | When using the Deals database |
| `AI Summary` | Text (Autofill) | Auto-generated from contact page body |
| `AI Next Action` | Text (Autofill) | Custom prompt: recommended next step |
| `First Name` / `Last Name` | Text | Split from Title when generating personalized outreach via Autofill |

---

## 2.3 Companies Database — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Company Name` | Title | Organization name |
| `Company Status` | Status | Relationship lifecycle |
| `Company Type` | Multi-select | Client / Prospect / Partner / Vendor / Investor |
| `Industry` | Select | Sector or vertical |
| `Website` | URL | Primary web presence |
| `Contacts` | Relation → Contacts DB | All people associated with this company |
| `Deals` | Relation → Deals DB | All deals associated with this company |
| `Company Owner` | Person | Who owns this relationship |
| `Company ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `CO-`) | Stable agent reference |
| `Contact Count` | Rollup → Contacts (Count) | How many contacts are associated |

### Status groups for Companies
```
To-do:        New, Researching
In progress:  Active, Engaged, In Negotiation
Complete:     Partner, Client, Inactive, Archived
```

---

## 2.4 Deals Database — Schema & Standards

**Add Deals when:** Multiple business cycles with the same company · Need to track deal value or close probability · Multiple people from same company in different deals.
**Skip Deals when:** One ongoing engagement per company (use Company record) · The "deal" is really a project (use Projects database).

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Deal Name` | Title | `[Company] — [Opportunity]` |
| `Deal Status` | Status | Pipeline stage |
| `Deal Value` | Number | Estimated or confirmed value |
| `Company` | Relation → Companies DB | Parent company |
| `Contacts` | Relation → Contacts DB | Humans involved in this deal |
| `Close Date` | Date | Target or actual close date |
| `Deal Owner` | Person | Who owns this deal |
| `Deal ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `DEAL-`) | Stable agent reference |
| `Probability` | Number (%) | Likelihood of close |

### Status groups for Deals — the pipeline
```
To-do:        Lead, Qualified
In progress:  Proposal Sent, In Negotiation, Contract Out
Complete:     Closed Won, Closed Lost, On Hold
```

### Weighted pipeline formula
```javascript
prop("Deal Value") * (prop("Probability") / 100)
```
Create a `Weighted Value` Number formula property. Roll it up in the Companies database for weighted pipeline by company.

---

## 2.5 Interactions Database — When to Add It

**Add when:** You need to filter by interaction type or date · Multiple people maintain relationships with the same contacts · Agents need to surface interaction patterns.

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Interaction Title` | Title | Date + type: `2026-03-04 — Call` |
| `Interaction Type` | Select | Call / Email / Meeting / Note / Event |
| `Interaction Date` | Date | When it happened |
| `Contact` | Relation → Contacts DB | Who was involved |
| `Deal` | Relation → Deals DB | Which deal, if applicable |
| `Summary` | Text | What happened, what was decided |
| `Next Step` | Text | What to do next |
| `Logged By` | Person | Who logged this |

---

## 2.6 Pipeline Stages as Status — Non-Negotiable

Three reasons:
1. **Filtering:** `Status group = In progress` captures all active pipeline stages instantly, survives renames
2. **Agent reasoning:** Agents can use `Status group = In progress` reliably without being taught option names
3. **Rollups:** Rolling up "count of active deals per company" works durably with group semantics

---

## 2.7 AI Autofill for Contact Enrichment
`Source: Official | Last verified: Mar 4, 2026 | Confidence: High`

**Autofill reads:** Page body only. Not file attachments, URL properties, or linked database entries. Does NOT read from the web.

**Minimum viable contact body:** How you know them · What they do / care about · History of interactions · Relevant constraints or preferences · Current status

### Recommended Autofill properties for Contacts

| Property | Autofill prompt |
|---|---|
| `AI Summary` | Summary — 2-3 sentences: who this contact is and current relationship state |
| `AI Next Action` | Custom: "Based on the interaction history and notes in this page, what is the single most important next action for this relationship?" |
| `AI Key Context` | Key Info — extract the most important facts relevant to ongoing engagement |

**Auto-update on page edits:** Enable for `AI Summary` — refreshes 5 minutes after page body changes.

---

## 2.8 Views — CRM

| View | Configuration | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Pipeline Board** | Group by `Deal Status` | Live deal pipeline |
| **Active Contacts** | Filter: Status group = In progress, sort by `Next Follow-up` | Relationship priority queue |
| **My Contacts** | Filter: `Contact Owner = Me`, Status group ≠ Complete | Personal relationship view |
| **Follow-up Due** | Filter: `Next Follow-up` ≤ today, Status group = In progress | Daily action queue |
| **Stale Contacts** | Filter: `Last Contacted` > 30 days ago, Status = Active | Relationship maintenance |

**Linked views inside pages:** Inside each Company page, add linked views of both Contacts and Deals filtered to that company. Every company page becomes a full relationship command center.

---

## 2.9 Page Body Standards — CRM

### Contact page body template
```
## Who They Are
[How you know them, what they do, what they care about]

## Relationship History
[Timeline of key interactions, decisions made, commitments given]

## Current Context
[Where things stand now — active asks, active opportunities, active projects]

## Key Facts
[Constraints, preferences, sensitivities, interests]

## Next Step
[The specific next action — if known]
```

### Company page body template
```
## What This Company Is
[What they do, why they matter to this workspace]

## Relationship Context
[How the relationship started, current state, key people involved]

## Active Opportunities / Deals
[Summary of anything in motion]

## Key Facts
[Constraints, preferences, budget signals, decision-making structure]
```

### Deal page body template
```
## What This Deal Is
[What we're trying to accomplish and for whom]

## Current Status
[Where we are in the process — most recent development]

## Key Stakeholders
[Who is involved, who makes the decision, who influences it]

## Blockers / Risks
[What could prevent this from closing]

## Definition of Closed Won
[Exactly what "won" looks like]
```

### Contact intake prompt (append to new contact pages)
```
## Intake — Please Complete
- [ ] How did you meet this person?
- [ ] What do they do / what do they care about?
- [ ] What's the context for this relationship?
- [ ] What's the immediate next step?
- [ ] Any key facts (constraints, preferences, sensitivities)?
```

---

## 2.10 Agent SOP Templates — Relationship Maintenance

### SOP 1: Stale Contact Flagging
```
SOP: Stale Relationship Agent — Follow-up Flagging
Goal: Flag contacts in Active or Nurturing status where Last Contacted > 30 days ago and no Next Follow-up is set
Inputs: Contacts DB, filtered: Status = Active OR Nurturing | Last Contacted < 30 days ago | Next Follow-up is empty
Allowed actions: Set Next Follow-up to today + 3 days | Append to page body: "[Agent] Flagged stale on [date]."
Hard constraints: Do not change Contact Status | Do not send any communication | Do not act on Archived or Inactive | Always log before acting
Validation: [ ] Last Contacted past threshold | [ ] Contact Owner exists | [ ] Status is Active or Nurturing
Logging: Agent Log: contact ID, name, Last Contacted date, Next Follow-up set to, timestamp
Escalation: If Contact Owner missing → skip, add to Agent Inbox
```

### SOP 2: Daily Follow-up Digest
```
SOP: Follow-up Digest Agent — Daily Relationship Queue
Goal: Post summary of all contacts and deals where follow-up is due today or overdue
Inputs: Contacts DB: Next Follow-up ≤ today, Status group = In progress | Deals DB: Close Date ≤ 14 days, Status group = In progress
Allowed actions: Read Contacts and Deals databases | Post formatted digest to Slack OR append to designated Notion inbox page
Hard constraints: Read only | If 0 items match: post "No follow-ups due today."
Validation: [ ] Both databases queried before posting | [ ] Message includes Name, Type, Due Date, Owner
Logging: Agent Log: timestamp, counts (contacts due, deals due), post confirmed
Escalation: If post fails → create Agent Inbox item with full digest content
```

### SOP 3: New Contact Intake
```
SOP: Contact Intake Agent — New Contact Triage
Goal: When new Contact row created with Status = New, append structured intake prompt to page body
Inputs: Contacts database, trigger: new row with Contact Status = New
Allowed actions: Append intake prompt to page body | Set Next Follow-up to today + 7 days if empty
Hard constraints: Do not change any properties other than Next Follow-up | Append only — never overwrite
Validation: [ ] Row created within last 60 minutes | [ ] Page body does not already contain intake prompt
Logging: Agent Log: contact ID, name, intake appended, follow-up set
Escalation: If Contact Owner missing → add to Agent Inbox: "New contact [name] has no owner assigned."
```

---

## 2.11 Common Mistakes — CRM

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Using Select for pipeline stages | Group filtering breaks; agents can't reason about state | Switch to Status |
| Building Deals before Contacts + Companies are operational | Orphaned deals with no relational context | Stabilize Contacts + Companies first |
| Empty contact page bodies | Autofill produces nothing; agents have no context | Enforce page body template at creation |
| Storing interaction history only in page bodies | Can't filter by type or date; agents can't surface patterns | Add Interactions DB when volume warrants it |
| One Contacts DB entry per role rather than per person | Duplicate records when people change jobs | One row per person; update Company relation when they move |
| Rollup using option name instead of Status group | Breaks on stage rename | Use `Status group = In progress` in all rollups |
| Merging Contacts and Companies | Can't roll up company-level metrics cleanly | Keep them separate; use Relation property |
| Not setting Contact Owner | Agents can't route; follow-up responsibility is unclear | Make Contact Owner a required field |

---

---

# DOC 3 — AI AGENTS: DEEP DIVE
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**
*Primary focus document for all agent work. Load alongside Doc 0 §7, §8, §13 for complete picture.*

**Agent scope:** Build, configure, debug, and optimize Personal Agent, Custom Agents, and agent infrastructure. Apply credit economics, prompt injection defense, and agent design patterns documented here.
**Agents must not:** Create new agents, modify existing agent Instructions pages, or expand agent permissions without explicit workspace owner instruction.

---

## 3.1 Agent Architecture Map

```
PERSONAL AGENT (reactive)
├── Instructions page (always-on constitution)
├── Skills (saved prompt templates)
└── Connected: Slack, Google Drive, Calendar, CSV, comments

CUSTOM AGENTS (autonomous, triggered)
├── Instructions page
├── SOP page(s)
├── Agent Log (audit trail)
├── Agent Inbox (human review queue)
├── Trigger: Schedule / Slack message / Email received / Database change
└── Actions: Read, Create, Update, Append, Move, Slack, Email, REST API, MCP

NOTION WORKERS (extreme pre-alpha — developer infrastructure via Vercel)
└── Watch: May 2026 announcement
```

---

## 3.2 Personal Agent vs Custom Agent — Decision Rule

| Use Personal Agent when... | Use Custom Agent when... |
|---|---|
| Task requires judgment or context from you | Task is repeatable with defined trigger conditions |
| One-time or occasional work | Ongoing workflow running without prompting |
| You need to review and direct mid-task | Fully autonomous execution is safe |
| Work involves creative or ambiguous decisions | Task follows clear if/then logic |

---

## 3.3 Custom Agents — Build Patterns

### One agent, one job — the non-negotiable design rule
Broad agents fail on: credit consumption, reasoning overhead, permissions blast radius, and error surface. A "general-purpose workspace agent" is a guaranteed failure mode.

### Trigger types

| Trigger | What fires it | Best use |
|---|---|---|
| **Schedule (cron)** | Time-based: daily, hourly, weekly | Digests, reviews, recurring checks |
| **Database change** | Row created or property updated | Intake flows, status-change responses |
| **Slack message** | Message to specific channel or @mention | Team-facing command interfaces |
| **Email received** | Email arrives in Notion Mail | Email-to-database triage flows |

### Action types — full whitelist reference

| Action | What it does | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Read filtered records | Query a database view | Most common; always specify filter |
| Create entry | Add a new row to a database | Requires all required properties; use Unique ID |
| Update property | Change a property value on existing row | Must target by Unique ID for reliability |
| Append to page body | Add content without overwriting | Preferred — always log first |
| Move page | Relocate a page to different parent | High-risk; always log |
| Send Slack message | Post to a channel or reply | Read-and-reply permission model |
| Send email | Send from Notion Mail | Requires explicit permission scope |
| Call REST API / webhook | Trigger external services | Use for Zapier, Make, etc. |
| Post via MCP | Interact with connected services | Linear, Figma, HubSpot, custom MCP servers |

### Required agent infrastructure stack — minimum viable
Every agent must have all five before being enabled:
1. **Instructions page** — scope, allowed actions, naming rules, hard constraints, escalation
2. **SOP page** — if X then Y logic, failure modes, validation checklist
3. **Agent Log** — audit trail: every run, timestamp, affected pages, fields changed, credits used
4. **Agent Inbox** — human review queue for uncertain or low-confidence actions
5. **Unique IDs** — all records the agent targets must have Unique ID properties configured

---

## 3.4 Credit Economics — Building Lean Agents

Credits go live May 4, 2026. Cost: $10 per 1,000 credits. Cost correlates with step count per run.

**Design principles for lean agents:**
- One job = fewer steps = lower cost per run
- Use MiniMax M2.5 for high-volume, simple tasks (up to 10x cost reduction vs premium models)
- Reserve GPT-5.2, Claude Opus 4.5/4.6 for complex reasoning tasks
- Split one broad agent into 3–5 single-purpose agents (lower cost per run, easier to debug, narrower permissions)
- Test step count before May 4 during the free beta window — measure everything

### Model selection guide

| Model | Best for | Cost profile |
|---|---|---|
| **MiniMax M2.5** | High-volume, simple, repeatable tasks | Up to 10x cheaper than premium |
| **GPT-5.2** | Complex multi-step reasoning, natural language generation | Premium |
| **Claude Opus 4.5 / 4.6** | Complex reasoning, structured writing, nuanced judgment | Premium |
| **Gemini 3** | Multi-modal tasks, web-connected research | Premium |
| **Auto** | Let Notion select based on task type | Variable |

**Rule:** MiniMax M2.5 for volume. Premium models for judgment.

---

## 3.5 Prompt Injection Defense

Notion's Custom Agents have built-in prompt injection detection. Additional design-level defenses:
- Never let agents read from untrusted public inputs (public form submissions, unmoderated comments) without a sanitization step
- Keep agent permissions scoped to only the databases they need
- **Agent Inbox pattern:** When confidence is low, agent writes to the Inbox for human review rather than acting
- Always log before acting — an action without a log entry never happened in the audit sense

---

## 3.6 MCP Layer — Notion as External AI Infrastructure

Notion's hosted MCP server makes the entire workspace accessible to external AI tools via OAuth. Schema consistency and naming conventions now determine what external AI can do. A workspace built to Codex standards is immediately operable by any MCP-capable tool.

**MCP-connected integrations (Custom Agents):** Linear · Figma · HubSpot · Slack · Notion Mail · Notion Calendar · custom MCP servers

---

## 3.7 Agent Templates — Ready to Deploy

### Template A: Database Intake Agent
```
Name: [DB Name] Intake Agent
Trigger: Database change — new row created in [target database]
Job: Append structured intake prompt to the new row's page body

Instructions:
- Scope: [target database] — new rows only
- Allowed actions: Read new row | Append intake template to page body
- If Next Follow-up / Due Date exists and is empty: set to today + [N] days
- Do not modify any existing page body content — append only
- Always log the run before acting

Validation:
- [ ] Row created within last 60 minutes
- [ ] Page body does not already contain the intake prompt

Logging: record ID, name, intake appended timestamp
Escalation: If Owner property missing → Agent Inbox item
```

### Template B: Digest Agent
```
Name: [Domain] Daily Digest
Trigger: Schedule — daily at [time]
Job: Query database for items requiring attention, post formatted summary

Instructions:
- Scope: [target database], filtered to [attention criteria]
- Allowed actions: Read database (filtered view) | Post to Slack channel: [specify]
- If 0 items match filter: post "No [items] require attention today."
- Read only — no writes to database

Validation:
- [ ] Query returns results before posting
- [ ] Message includes: Name, Owner, Due Date, Status

Logging: timestamp, item count, Slack post confirmed
Escalation: If Slack post fails → Agent Inbox item
```

### Template C: Status Flag Agent
```
Name: [Status] Flag Agent
Trigger: Schedule — [daily/hourly]
Job: Identify records meeting a condition, update Status or append a flag

Instructions:
- Scope: [target database], filtered to [specific condition]
- Allowed actions: Update [Status property] to [target value] | Append: "[Agent] [action] on [date]. Was: [previous value]."
- Hard constraint: Do not act if Status already [target value], Done, or Cancelled
- Always log before acting

Validation:
- [ ] Condition is genuinely met (not a data artifact)
- [ ] Record has an Owner assigned
- [ ] Record is not in a Complete group

Logging: record ID, name, previous status, new status, timestamp
Escalation: If Owner missing → skip, Agent Inbox item
```

---

## 3.8 Common Mistakes — Agent Builds

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| One broad agent trying to do everything | High credit cost, high error rate, wide permissions blast radius | Split into single-purpose agents |
| No Unique IDs on target databases | Agent targets wrong record or can't find record | Enable Unique ID on all agent-targeted databases |
| No Agent Log | No audit trail; can't debug errors | Build Agent Log before enabling agent |
| No Agent Inbox | Uncertain actions execute without human review | Build Agent Inbox; escalate low-confidence cases |
| Instructions page not machine-parseable | Agent interprets instructions inconsistently | Rewrite in bullet blocks; remove prose narration |
| Agent reads from untrusted input sources | Prompt injection vulnerability | Add sanitization step; scope permissions narrowly |
| Testing agents after May 4, 2026 | Unexpected credit costs | Test everything before May 4 during free beta |
| Overwriting page body content | Destroys existing notes and context | Use Append action, never Replace/Overwrite |

---

---

# DOC 4 — CONTENT & PUBLISHING
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

**Agent scope:** Build or audit Content Calendar database, configure editorial workflows, set up Autofill for briefs and summaries, write agent SOPs for content triage.
**Agents must not:** Publish content externally, delete content records, or alter platform tracking data without explicit instruction.

---

## 4.1 Content System Architecture

```
CONTENT CALENDAR DB (source)
├── Tracks: every piece of content from idea to published
├── Relations: Projects DB, Asset Library DB
└── Autofill: AI Brief from page body notes

ASSET LIBRARY DB (child)
├── Linked to: Content Calendar entry
└── Tracks: File reference, version, format, approval status

PLATFORM TRACKER DB (optional child)
└── Per-platform publish status and performance
```

---

## 4.2 Content Calendar — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Content Title` | Title | Working title — be specific |
| `Content Status` | Status | Editorial lifecycle stage |
| `Content Type` | Select | Article / Video / Short / Thread / Podcast / Email / Template |
| `Platform` | Multi-select | Where this content is published |
| `Publish Date` | Date | Target or actual publish date |
| `Content Owner` | Person | Single responsible creator |
| `Content ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `CNT-`) | Stable reference for agents |
| `Project` | Relation → Projects DB | Which project this content belongs to |
| `AI Brief` | Text (Autofill) | Auto-generated brief from page body |
| `AI Summary` | Text (Autofill) | Post-draft summary |

### Status groups for Content Calendar
```
To-do:        Idea, Briefed, Scripted
In progress:  In Production, In Review, Scheduled
Complete:     Published, Archived, Cancelled
```

### Optional properties

| Property | Type | When to add |
|---|---|---|
| `Series` | Relation → Content Calendar (self) | Content belonging to a series |
| `Deadline` | Date | Hard external deadline vs target Publish Date |
| `Collab` | Relation → Contacts DB | When a collaborator or guest is involved |
| `Asset Count` | Rollup → Asset Library (Count) | Tracking deliverable completeness |

---

## 4.3 Status-Driven Editorial Workflow

```
Idea → brief is written and approved
Briefed → scripting/writing begins
Scripted → production begins (recording, design, etc.)
In Production → in review by owner or collaborator
In Review → scheduled in platform
Scheduled → published
Published → Archive or leave in Published
```

**Agent-readable rule:** Use `Status group = In progress` to capture Scripted, In Production, In Review, and Scheduled in one reliable filter — not option names.

---

## 4.4 Autofill for Content

### AI Brief — before production
```
Autofill custom prompt:
Based on the notes in this page, generate a production brief for this content piece. Include:
- Core message / thesis
- Target audience
- Key points to cover (3-5 bullets)
- Tone and format guidance
- Any constraints or requirements mentioned
```
**Requirement:** Page body must contain content idea, angle, research notes, or context before triggering Autofill. Empty page body = empty brief.

### AI Summary — after drafting
```
Summary — 2-3 sentences summarizing what this content piece is about and its core argument or value.
```
Enable "Auto-update on page edits" for `AI Summary` — refreshes as the draft evolves.

---

## 4.5 Views — Content Calendar

| View | Configuration | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Editorial Calendar** | Calendar, date = `Publish Date`, color by `Platform` | See what's publishing when |
| **Production Board** | Board, group by `Content Status` | Daily execution |
| **My Content** | Filter: `Content Owner = Me`, Status group ≠ Complete | Personal production queue |
| **Platform View** | Filter by specific `Platform`, sort by `Publish Date` | Platform-specific planning |
| **Ideas Backlog** | Filter: Content Status = Idea, sort by Created time | Idea prioritization |
| **Published** | Filter: Content Status = Published, sort by `Publish Date` desc | Archive and reference |

---

## 4.6 Page Body Standards — Content

### Idea / brief stage
```
## Content Idea
[What this piece is about — one clear sentence]

## Angle / Hook
[What makes this specific, compelling, different from generic content on this topic]

## Target Audience
[Who this is for and what they need from it]

## Key Points
- [Point 1]
- [Point 2]
- [Point 3]

## Research / Notes
[Links, quotes, data, references]

## Constraints
[Deadline, format, length, collaborators, platform-specific requirements]
```

### Post-production additions
```
## Draft Link
[Link to draft document, script, or recording]

## Review Notes
[Feedback received, changes made]

## Final Asset
[Link to final file or embed]

## Publish Notes
[Where published, URL, any performance notes]
```

---

## 4.7 Agent SOP — Content Triage
```
SOP: Content Triage Agent — Status and Brief Management
Trigger: Schedule — daily at [time] OR database change (new row with Status = Idea)
Job: For new Idea rows: append brief intake template | For stale In Progress items: flag for review

Allowed actions (new intake):
- Append brief intake template to page body
- Set Publish Date to today + [default lead time] if empty

Allowed actions (stale flag):
- Append: "[Agent] Flagged as stale on [date]. In [Status] since [last edited date]."
- Set Content Status to "Blocked" if stale > 14 days with no activity

Hard constraints: Read only on stale items unless flagging Blocked | No deletions | No writes to Published items | Always log

Logging: Agent Log: content ID, title, action taken, timestamp
Escalation: If Content Owner missing → Agent Inbox item
```

---

## 4.8 Common Mistakes — Content System

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Using Select for Content Status | Workflow filtering breaks | Switch to Status |
| Empty page bodies | AI Brief produces nothing; agents have no context | Enforce page body intake at idea creation |
| One database per platform | Fragmented pipeline; no cross-platform view | One Content Calendar, Platform as Multi-select |
| No Publish Date on content | Can't build editorial calendar view | Make Publish Date required in page template |
| Autofill configured before page body standards | Hallucinated briefs | Set page body template first, then configure Autofill |

---

---

# DOC 5 — WIKI & KNOWLEDGE BASE
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

**Agent scope:** Build or audit knowledge base architecture, optimize pages for Q&A, set up governance and naming conventions.
**Agents must not:** Delete or archive knowledge pages, restructure the sidebar, or change page permissions without explicit instruction.

---

## 5.1 Information Architecture Principles

```
Layer 1: NAVIGATION (sidebar + top-level pages)
         — What exists; how to get around
         — Must be legible in 60 seconds

Layer 2: REFERENCE (databases + structured pages)
         — What is true; schemas, specs, SOPs, decisions
         — Optimized for search and Q&A retrieval

Layer 3: WORKING MEMORY (page bodies + active docs)
         — What is happening; drafts, notes, project context
         — Updated continuously; archived when stale
```

### Sidebar architecture rules
- Maximum 3 levels of nesting in sidebar
- Top-level items = major domains (Projects, CRM, Content, Knowledge, Operations)
- Never put source databases in the sidebar — put linked views on overview pages
- Every top-level section should have one orientation page

### Page naming conventions
- **Databases:** Plural nouns — `Projects`, `Contacts`, `Content Calendar`
- **Overview pages:** `[Domain] Home` or `[Domain] Overview`
- **Reference pages:** Descriptive, specific — `Sprint Architecture — How Sprints Work`
- **Working documents:** Date-prefixed if time-sensitive — `2026-03-04 Weekly Review`
- **Never:** `Notes`, `Misc`, `Temp`, `Old`

---

## 5.2 Q&A Optimization

### What Q&A does well
- Finding pages by topic or keyword
- Surfacing information written in page body paragraphs
- Answering factual questions when the answer exists in a page body
- Searching across Enterprise-connected tools (Slack, Google Drive, GitHub)

### What Q&A does not do well
- Counting records in a database
- Aggregating numerical values
- Filtering by property values
- Precise lookup of structured data

### Design rules for Q&A-ready pages
- **Page title = the question the page answers.** `"How do agents work in this workspace?"` rather than `"Agent Info"`
- **Opening paragraph = the answer.** Put the core answer first — don't bury it
- **Keep pages recently updated.** Q&A prioritizes freshness
- **Write in sentences, not only bullets.** Q&A retrieves prose better than fragmented bullet points
- **Use specific, descriptive headings.** They improve Q&A retrieval accuracy

---

## 5.3 Database vs Page — The Decision Rule

| Use a database when... | Use a page when... |
|---|---|
| You have ≥10 similar items to track | You have one document, not a collection |
| Items need properties (owner, date, status) | The item is prose-heavy with no structured properties |
| You need to filter, sort, or group items | The document is standalone |
| Items relate to other databases | Q&A is the primary access method |
| Agents need to act on items by property | You need to write and read a single reference |

---

## 5.4 Knowledge Base Schema

### Reference wiki page template
```
# [Page Title — written as the question this page answers]
**Last verified:** [date] | **Owner:** [person] | **Status:** [Current / Needs Review]

## Summary
[1-2 sentences: what this page is and why it matters]

## [Main content section]
[Body content, structured logically]

## Related pages
- [Link]

## Changelog
- [date] — [what changed]
```

### Knowledge database (when items need properties)

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Article Title` | Title | What this knowledge item is about |
| `Article Status` | Status | Current / Needs Review / Outdated / Archived |
| `Category` | Multi-select | Domain classification |
| `Owner` | Person | Who maintains this |
| `Last Reviewed` | Date | When someone last verified accuracy |
| `Article ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `KB-`) | Stable agent reference |
| `AI Summary` | Text (Autofill) | Auto-generated summary from page body |

### Status groups for Knowledge items
```
To-do:        Draft, Needs Review
In progress:  In Progress, Under Revision
Complete:     Current, Archived
```

---

## 5.5 Governance — Anti-Rot Mechanisms

### Weekly review survival mechanism
```
1. CAPTURE: All loose notes, tasks, and ideas are in the system
2. TRIAGE: Every new inbox item has a status and owner
3. SCHEDULE: Everything due this week is on the calendar or in the sprint
4. NORMALIZE: Audit property values for consistency (Status, names, etc.)
5. PRUNE: Archive or delete views, pages, and entries no longer needed
6. UPDATE: Flag Doc 0 if any platform fundamentals have changed
```

**Rule:** The weekly review is not optional. It is the maintenance mechanism that prevents accumulation of chaos.

### Staleness protocol
- Set `Last Reviewed` date property on all reference pages
- Any page with `Last Reviewed` > 60 days → trigger review
- Pages with Status = "Needs Review" surface in a dedicated linked view for triage

### Archiving rules
- Never delete — archive instead (except truly temporary working documents)
- Archive = move to Archive section OR set Status = Archived
- Archived pages are excluded from main navigation views but remain searchable
- Review the archive quarterly

---

## 5.6 Enterprise Search Configuration

Enterprise Search indexes: Notion workspace + Slack + Google Drive + GitHub (beta). Requires Enterprise plan + connecting each tool in Workspace Settings → Integrations.

Permissions are respected — users only see content they have access to in the connected tool.

---

## 5.7 Common Mistakes — Wiki & Knowledge Base

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Too many nesting levels in sidebar | Nobody can find anything | Cap at 3 levels; flatten with linked views on hub pages |
| Databases for everything | Simple reference docs become property-heavy overhead | Use pages for prose; databases for items with lifecycle |
| Vague page names | Q&A can't retrieve accurately; humans can't orient | Rename pages as the question they answer |
| No weekly review | Knowledge base decays; stale content takes over | Schedule weekly review; make it non-optional |
| Deleting instead of archiving | Loses history; broken links | Always archive |
| Empty page bodies in databases | Q&A and Autofill produce nothing | Enforce page body template for every database |
| No Last Reviewed tracking | No visibility into what's stale | Add Last Reviewed date to all reference pages |

---

---

# DOC 6 — AUTOMATIONS & INTEGRATIONS
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

**Agent scope:** Build or audit native automations, configure webhook connections, document API workflows, design automation vs agent decision logic.
**Agents must not:** Create or modify webhook connections, modify native automation rules, or change external integration credentials without explicit instruction.

---

## 6.1 Automation vs Agent — The Decision Rule

| Use native automation when... | Use an agent when... |
|---|---|
| Logic is simple: if X then Y | Logic requires reasoning or judgment |
| Trigger is a property change or button click | Task involves reading/summarizing/generating |
| Actions are deterministic (set a property, send a notification) | Multiple steps depend on prior outputs |
| Speed matters (automations run in seconds) | Context matters more than speed |
| No content generation needed | Content generation is the output |

**The pattern:** Automation handles mechanical workflow routing. Agents handle anything requiring intelligence. They work together: automation triggers an agent; agent produces output; automation routes the result.

---

## 6.2 Native Automation Engine

### Trigger types

| Trigger | What fires it | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **Button** | User clicks a button in a page or database | "Create next sprint", "Send to review" |
| **Property change** | A property value is updated | When Status changes to "Published" → notify Slack |
| **Page added to database** | A new row is created | When new Contact created → set Next Follow-up |
| **Date trigger** | A specific date or date property is reached | When Publish Date = today → send reminder |

### Action types

| Action | Notes |
|---|---|
| **Edit a page** | Update properties, move to section |
| **Add a page** | Create a new page in a database or section |
| **Send a Slack notification** | To a channel; requires Slack integration |
| **Send an email** | Via Notion Mail |
| **Send a webhook** | POST to any URL — connects to Zapier, Make, or any REST endpoint |
| **Grant/revoke access** | Add or remove user permissions |

### Webhook action — the bridge to 1,000+ tools
Automation → Actions → Send a webhook → Enter webhook URL from Zapier, Make, or your endpoint. Payload includes: page ID, database ID, property values, timestamp. External tool receives the webhook and executes its workflow.

---

## 6.3 Native Integrations — Deep Reference

### Slack
- Two-way: read and post to channels, DMs, threads
- Custom Agents: can read Slack messages as triggers; can post formatted messages
- Personal Agent: can read and post to connected channels, search message history
- Automation: trigger on Notion property change → post to Slack channel

### Jira
`Source: Official | Last verified: Mar 4, 2026 | Confidence: High`
- Bi-directional sync (Notion 3.2)
- Configuration: Workspace Settings → Integrations → Jira → connect workspace
- Fields that sync: Title, Status, Assignee, Priority, Due Date

### GitHub
- Enterprise Search: Q&A can answer questions about PRs, issues, and repository content
- AI answers from GitHub (beta): natural language queries about code and repository state
- Automation: Webhook from GitHub → Notion automation to create/update database entries

### Google Drive
- Personal Agent connected tool: agent can read Google Doc content and use as context
- Enterprise Search: Q&A indexes Google Drive documents within permissions
- Agents cannot read file contents directly via URL property — only via the Personal Agent connection

### Figma
- Custom Agent native integration: agents can read Figma files and post comments

### Linear
- Custom Agent native integration: agents can read and create Linear issues
- Use case: engineering sprints where Linear is the execution layer; Notion is planning and context

### HubSpot
- Custom Agent native integration: agents can read HubSpot contact and deal data
- Use Notion as context and relationship intelligence layer; HubSpot as execution layer for email tracking and call logging

### Zapier / Make
- Use via webhook automation action — no dedicated native connector needed
- Best for: tools not covered by native integrations or MCP servers

---

## 6.4 The Notion API
`Source: Official (developers.notion.com) | Last verified: Mar 4, 2026 | Confidence: High`

### Core capabilities
- Read databases, pages, and blocks
- Create and update pages and database entries
- Query databases with filters, sorts, and pagination
- Search across the workspace
- Manage comments and page history

### Authentication
- **Internal integrations:** API key (Integration token) — simplest for personal and internal use
- **Public integrations:** OAuth 2.0 — required for tools used by others

### Key API patterns
```javascript
// Read a database with a filter
GET /databases/{database_id}/query
Body: {
  "filter": {
    "property": "Status",
    "status": { "equals": "In Progress" }
  }
}

// Create a new page in a database
POST /pages
Body: {
  "parent": { "database_id": "{database_id}" },
  "properties": {
    "Task Name": { "title": [{ "text": { "content": "New task title" } }] },
    "Task Status": { "status": { "name": "Not Started" } }
  }
}
```

### API limitations to design around
- Rate limit: 3 requests per second
- Block children: max 100 per request; paginate for longer pages
- Files: upload via external URL; Notion does not host files via API

---

## 6.5 Automation Decision Framework — By Use Case

| Use case | Best approach |
|---|---|
| Set a property when another property changes | Native automation — property trigger |
| Notify Slack when a task is overdue | Native automation (date trigger) → Slack action |
| Create a new entry from a button click | Native automation — button trigger |
| Summarize new database entries | Custom Agent — database change trigger |
| Enrich contacts with research notes | Personal Agent — prompted on demand |
| Sync data to an external system | Native automation → webhook → Zapier/Make |
| Pull data from GitHub into Notion | GitHub native integration + Enterprise Search |
| Complex multi-step workflow with conditionals | Custom Agent — schedule or database change trigger |
| API-powered custom integration | Notion API + external service |

---

## 6.6 Common Mistakes — Automations & Integrations

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Building agent logic for simple property routing | Unnecessary credit cost; slower than automation | Use native automation for if X then Y |
| No webhook payload inspection before building | Integration sends wrong fields | Test webhook payload in Zapier/Make first |
| API calls without pagination | Misses records beyond the first 100 | Always paginate API queries on large databases |
| Automations without logging | Can't audit what fired and when | Add a log entry to every automation action |
| Webhook secrets not configured | Security exposure | Configure webhook authentication token |

---

---

# DOC 7 — ART & CREATIVE PRODUCTION
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

**Agent scope:** Build or audit commission tracking, creative brief database, asset library, collaborator management. Write agent SOPs for deliverable tracking and brief generation.
**Agents must not:** Delete commission records, alter contract or payment data, or communicate with collaborators on behalf of the workspace owner without explicit instruction.

---

## 7.1 Creative Production Architecture

```
COMMISSIONS DB (parent)
├── Relations: Contacts DB (collaborators), Asset Library DB (deliverables), Projects DB
├── Tracks: Brief, contract status, payment, deadlines
└── Autofill: AI Brief from page body notes

ASSET LIBRARY DB (child)
├── Linked to: Commission record
├── Tracks: File reference, version, format, approval status
└── Gallery view for visual browsing

COLLABORATORS
└── Use Contacts DB (Doc 2) with Contact Type = Collaborator
   Do not create a separate database
```

---

## 7.2 Commissions Database — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Commission Title` | Title | `[Client] — [Deliverable]` |
| `Commission Status` | Status | Production lifecycle |
| `Collaborator` | Relation → Contacts DB | Artist, designer, or creator |
| `Commission Type` | Select | Illustration / Animation / Design / Photography / Music / Writing |
| `Brief Status` | Select | Draft / Approved / Final |
| `Contract Signed?` | Checkbox | Has the contract been executed |
| `Payment Status` | Select | Unpaid / Deposit Paid / Paid in Full |
| `Deadline` | Date | Hard delivery deadline |
| `Commission ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `COM-`) | Stable agent reference |
| `Assets` | Relation → Asset Library DB | Linked deliverable files |
| `Project` | Relation → Projects DB | Parent project, if applicable |

### Status groups for Commissions
```
To-do:        Inquiry, Brief Stage
In progress:  In Production, In Review, Revision Requested
Complete:     Approved, Delivered, Cancelled
```

### Optional properties

| Property | Type | When to add |
|---|---|---|
| `Commission Value` | Number | Tracking revenue or budget |
| `Usage Rights` | Select | Personal / Commercial / Exclusive |
| `Revision Count` | Number | Track how many revision rounds |
| `AI Brief` | Text (Autofill) | Auto-generated brief from page body notes |
| `Royalty Rate` | Number (%) | When royalty arrangements are in place |

---

## 7.3 Asset Library — Schema & Standards

### Required properties

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Asset Name` | Title | `[Commission ID] — [Asset Type] — v[N]` |
| `Asset Status` | Status | Review lifecycle |
| `Commission` | Relation → Commissions DB | Parent commission |
| `File Reference` | URL | Link to cloud storage (Google Drive, Dropbox, etc.) |
| `Format` | Select | PNG / JPG / SVG / MP4 / PDF / PSD / AI / Other |
| `Version` | Number | Version number |
| `Asset ID` | Unique ID (prefix: `AST-`) | Stable reference |

### Status groups for Assets
```
To-do:        Pending Delivery
In progress:  Submitted, In Review
Complete:     Approved, Rejected
```

**File reference pattern:** Store all final assets in Google Drive, Dropbox, or similar. The URL property in the Asset Library is the link to the external file. This keeps Notion fast and avoids file size limits. Notion cannot host large production files reliably.

**Primary view:** Gallery view — use Notion cover images where preview is possible. Use consistent naming scheme for visual identification.

---

## 7.4 Creative Brief — Autofill Configuration

### Commission page body template (enables good Autofill output)
```
## What This Commission Is
[What we're making and why — one clear statement of purpose]

## Creative Direction
[Visual style, tone, references, mood — be specific]

## Deliverables
- [Asset 1: format, dimensions, quantity]
- [Asset 2: format, dimensions, quantity]

## Audience
[Who will see or use this; what they need to feel or understand]

## Key Constraints
[Deadline, revision rounds allowed, brand guidelines, content restrictions]

## Reference Links
- [Inspiration / moodboard links]
- [Brand guidelines]
- [Prior work by this collaborator]

## Notes
[Anything else the collaborator needs to know]
```

### AI Brief Autofill prompt
```
Based on the creative brief notes in this page, generate a polished creative brief for this commission. Include:
- Project overview (2-3 sentences)
- Creative direction and style guidance
- Deliverable specifications
- Audience and purpose
- Key constraints and requirements
Format as a client-ready brief.
```

---

## 7.5 Collaborator Management

Use the Contacts database (Doc 2) with `Contact Type = Collaborator`. Do not build a separate database.

**Collaborator-specific additions:**
- Tag `Contact Type` as Collaborator
- Add `Portfolio` URL property if not already present
- Use page body for: medium and specialty, rate information, style notes, prior work references, communication preferences

**Rollup:** Add `Commission Count` Rollup → Commissions DB (Count) on the Contacts database to see full commission history per collaborator.

---

## 7.6 Contract and Payment Tracking

### Simple tracking (within Commissions DB — sufficient for most workflows)
- `Contract Signed?` — Checkbox
- `Payment Status` — Select: Unpaid / Deposit Paid / Paid in Full
- `Contract Link` — URL → external document (Google Doc, DocuSign, etc.)

### Full Contracts database (add when managing multiple contracts per commission or needing independent audit trail)

| Property | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Contract Title` | Title | `[Commission ID] — Contract v[N]` |
| `Contract Status` | Status | Draft / Sent / Signed / Expired |
| `Commission` | Relation → Commissions DB | Parent commission |
| `Contract Link` | URL | External document link |
| `Signed Date` | Date | When executed |
| `Expiry Date` | Date | When contract expires |

---

## 7.7 Agent SOP Templates — Creative Production

### SOP: Deliverable Tracking Agent
```
SOP: Deliverable Tracking Agent — Overdue Commission Flagging
Trigger: Schedule — daily at [time]
Job: Flag commissions where Deadline is past and Commission Status is still In Production or In Review

Inputs: Commissions database, filtered: Deadline < today, Commission Status = In Production OR In Review

Allowed actions:
- Append: "[Agent] Commission flagged overdue on [date]. Deadline was [deadline date]. Status: [current status]."
- Create Agent Inbox item with commission details for owner review

Hard constraints: Do not change Commission Status | Do not contact collaborators | Do not modify payment or contract properties | Always log before acting

Logging: Agent Log: commission ID, title, deadline, status, timestamp
Escalation: All flagged items → Agent Inbox for owner review
```

### SOP: Asset Intake Agent
```
SOP: Asset Intake Agent — New Asset Review Queue
Trigger: Database change — new row in Asset Library with Status = Submitted
Job: Notify owner that a new asset has been submitted for review

Allowed actions:
- Read new Asset record and parent Commission record
- Post Slack notification: "[Asset Name] has been submitted for review. Commission: [Commission Title]. Deadline: [date]."
- Set Asset Status to "In Review"

Hard constraints: Do not approve or reject assets | Do not contact collaborators

Logging: Agent Log: asset ID, asset name, commission linked, Slack post confirmed
Escalation: If Commission relation is empty → Agent Inbox item
```

---

## 7.8 Common Mistakes — Art & Creative Production

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Storing final files in Notion | Notion slows with large file attachments; files not readable by AI | Use Google Drive / Dropbox; store URL in Asset Library |
| One commission per deliverable instead of per engagement | Cluttered database; no overview of full project scope | One Commission per engagement; multiple Assets per Commission |
| Not filling out the brief page body | AI Brief Autofill produces nothing | Enforce brief template before setting Status = In Production |
| Managing collaborators in a separate database from Contacts | Duplicate records; no unified relationship view | Use Contacts DB with Contact Type = Collaborator |
| No contract tracking | Unclear whether agreements are in place | Add Contract Signed? checkbox as minimum |
| Revision rounds not tracked | Scope creep; unclear how many rounds are included | Add Revision Count number property |

---

---

# DOC 8 — PARTNERING & SUCCEEDING WITH NOTION
**v1.0 | March 4, 2026**

---

## 8.1 The Partnership Landscape — Two Paths

### Solutions Partner Program
Enterprise implementation pathway. Two tracks:
- **Sell:** Refer and sell Notion Enterprise licenses. Revenue share on referrals.
- **Service:** Build, implement, and maintain Notion systems for enterprise clients. Certification-gated access to enterprise deal flow.

**Who it's for:** Consultants and agencies who implement Notion at scale for enterprise organizations.

**Requirements:** Active client projects demonstrating implementation capability · Completion of Solutions Partner certification (Notion Academy) · Ongoing client volume requirements · Apply at notion.com/partners

### Ambassador Program
Community and education pathway for creators, educators, and template publishers.

**Contribution tracks:** Educational content (tutorials, YouTube, courses) · Template creation and Marketplace publication · Community engagement (forum answers, events, local meetups) · Building in public (live workspace builds, streams, cohorts)

**Requirements:** Monthly contribution minimum · Cohort review process — applications reviewed in batches · Track record required before application

**What Ambassadors get:** Early access to new features · ambassador badge · community visibility · co-marketing opportunities · direct Notion team relationships

### Decision rule

| If you are... | Go to... |
|---|---|
| Building enterprise systems for clients | Solutions Partner |
| Creating content, templates, or educational material | Ambassador |
| Both | Both programs are viable simultaneously — they are not exclusive |
| Building publicly toward formal partnership | Ambassador as primary entry point; Solutions Partner when client work is established |

---

## 8.2 Template Marketplace — Strategy and Standards

### What gets traction
- **Solves a specific, concrete problem.** Vague "productivity systems" compete with thousands. Specific solutions (sprint board for solo creators, CRM for consultants, commission tracker for artists) win.
- **Works out of the box.** Every property, view, and automation must be configured. No setup required from the user.
- **Includes a clear README page.** What this template does, how to set it up (2-3 steps), key databases and views.
- **Uses proper Notion architecture.** Status (not Select) for workflows, proper relations, Unique IDs — signals expertise and behaves better for users.
- **Has a demonstration screenshot or video.** Thumbnail quality is the #1 factor in click-through rate.

### Pricing guidance
- **Free:** Best for building visibility and Marketplace presence. Lead with free.
- **Paid ($9–$49):** Justifiable when the template is complex, saves significant setup time, and includes documentation. Price based on the time it saves, not the time you spent building it.
- **Template bundles:** Multiple related templates at a discount. Higher perceived value.

### Template maintenance
- Update when Notion ships major feature changes
- Use a Changelog page within the template to document versions
- Respond to user questions in the Notion community — visibility and reputation compound

---

## 8.3 Content Strategy for Partnership Growth

### High-value content types

| Content type | Why it works | Platform |
|---|---|---|
| **Workspace builds in public** | Shows system thinking, not just templates | YouTube, Twitch, X |
| **Template walkthroughs** | Drives Marketplace traffic and conversions | YouTube |
| **AI + Notion tutorials** | High demand; differentiates from older Notion content | YouTube, newsletter |
| **Enterprise Notion case studies** | Demonstrates Solutions Partner-level capability | LinkedIn, newsletter |
| **"How I built X in Notion"** | Specific, replicable, searchable | YouTube, X |

**The compound effect:** Notion content compounds because: the audience self-selects (high-intent users), templates build passive income and SEO, and every published build is public evidence for partnership applications.

### Community engagement
- **Notion forums and Reddit (r/notion):** Answer questions publicly; link to templates or content when relevant
- **Notion-focused Discord and Slack communities:** Build peer relationships; collaborate on builds
- **Local Notion events / meetups:** Ambassador program values in-person community contribution

---

## 8.4 Enterprise Notion — Super Admin Context

For enterprise Notion Super Admins (150+ person orgs):

### Admin-level capabilities
- **SAML SSO and SCIM provisioning:** User lifecycle management integrated with identity providers
- **Member management at scale:** Bulk operations, group permissions, guest management
- **Workspace analytics:** Page activity, member engagement, AI usage dashboards (Notion 3.2+)
- **Database row permissions:** Different members see different rows in the same database
- **Audit log:** Full record of workspace activity for compliance

### Sprint infrastructure at scale (40+ person teams)
- One Task database per team or functional area — not one global Task database (performance and permissions degrade at scale)
- Sprints database shared across teams for cross-team planning visibility
- Sprint board linked views on team hub pages — each team sees only their sprint
- Agent: Sprint summary digest to team Slack channel at end of each sprint
- Agent: Overdue task flagging runs daily per team database

### Governance at enterprise scale
- Workspace owner defines naming conventions globally, documented in Workspace Standards page
- Schema changes to shared databases require workspace owner approval
- All new databases must be initialized from a template including required properties (Status, Owner, Unique ID, Date)
- Audit guest access quarterly — Notion charges per guest above threshold

---

## 8.5 Partnership Application Readiness Checklist

### For Solutions Partner
- [ ] At least 2 active enterprise Notion clients with documented implementations
- [ ] Completed Notion Solutions Partner certification (Notion Academy)
- [ ] Case study or portfolio page showing workspace architecture, scale, and outcomes
- [ ] Dedicated Notion partnership landing page or clear positioning

### For Ambassador
- [ ] At least 6 months of consistent public Notion content
- [ ] Published at least 3 templates on the Notion Marketplace
- [ ] Active community presence (forum, Discord, or local)
- [ ] Clear content focus (Notion AI, enterprise builds, specific use case)
- [ ] Audience growth trajectory demonstrating ongoing momentum

---

## 8.6 Common Mistakes — Partnership Strategy

| Mistake | What goes wrong | The fix |
|---|---|---|
| Applying before building public proof | Applications rejected without track record | Build the evidence first; apply when proof exists |
| Creating general "productivity" templates | Compete against thousands; low conversion | Build specific-use-case templates with clear target audience |
| Building for the portfolio rather than for actual users | Templates that look good but don't work | Test every template with a real user before publishing |
| Treating Ambassador and Solutions Partner as competing | Miss the opportunity to pursue both | Apply both strategies; they reinforce each other |
| No Changelog on templates | Users confused when templates change | Maintain a Changelog page inside every published template |
| Ignoring the Notion community | Slow audience growth; no peer relationships | Engage consistently in forums, Discord, and local events |

---

